# find the graphics card on macOS
system_profiler SPDisplaysDataType

# get the latest ollama release
curl -L -R -O https://github.com/ollama/ollama/releases/download/v0.5.4/ollama-darwin
chmod 755 ./ollama-darwin

# start ollama
./ollama-darwin serve 2>&1 | tee ollama-darwin-serve.log

# pull a model
./ollama-darwin pull llama3.1:8b

# run a model
./ollama-darwin run llama3.1:8b

# list models
./ollama-darwin list

# remove a model
./ollama-darwin rm llama3.1:8b


# MODEL PICKS FOR AN 8 GB VRAM GPU (e.g. RTX 2000 Ada Laptop, RTX 3060
# Mobile 6/8 GB, 3070/4060 Laptop, etc.)
#
# sweet spot: 7B-8B models at Q4_K_M / Q5_K_M quantization. weights take
# 4-6 GB, leaving 2-3 GB for the KV cache (good for 4k-8k context).
# anything 13B+ requires Q3 and starts feeling cramped; sub-4B models
# run at higher quality (Q6/Q8) and feel snappy.
#
# expect ~30-50 tok/s on a 7B Q4 model on the RTX 2000 Ada (bandwidth
# bound around 224 GB/s).

# GENERAL CHAT / REASONING
ollama run qwen2.5:7b              # ~4.7 GB, strong all-rounder, long context
ollama run llama3.1:8b             # ~4.9 GB, solid tool-use, Meta workhorse
ollama run deepseek-r1:7b          # ~4.7 GB, chain-of-thought reasoning (R1 distill)
ollama run gemma2:9b               # ~5.4 GB, fits but tighter KV-cache budget
ollama run phi3.5:3.8b             # ~2.2 GB, punches above its weight, very fast

# CODE
ollama run qwen2.5-coder:7b        # ~4.7 GB, the standout small-model code generator
ollama run deepseek-coder-v2:16b   # MoE, ~9 GB — TIGHT, may swap to RAM; try if curious
ollama run codellama:7b            # ~3.8 GB, older but stable

# VISION / MULTIMODAL (image-in, text-out)
ollama run llama3.2-vision:11b     # ~7.9 GB — fits, but no headroom for big context
ollama run llava:7b                # ~4.7 GB, older but reliable
ollama run minicpm-v:8b            # ~5.5 GB, strong OCR / document understanding

# EMBEDDINGS (for RAG; tiny, run alongside a chat model)
ollama pull nomic-embed-text       # ~270 MB, 768-dim, great default
ollama pull bge-m3                 # ~1.2 GB, multilingual, 1024-dim
ollama pull mxbai-embed-large      # ~670 MB, 1024-dim, high MTEB scores

# WHAT NOT TO TRY ON 8 GB
#   Mistral Nemo 12B, Codestral 22B, Llama 3.x 70B, Qwen 2.5 32B+,
#   DeepSeek-V3, Mixtral 8x7B — all need more VRAM or aggressive
#   offload that destroys throughput.

# TIPS
#   ollama ps                          # see what's loaded + VRAM use
#   ollama show qwen2.5-coder:7b       # see context window, quant, template
#   OLLAMA_KEEP_ALIVE=24h ollama serve # keep model resident between requests
#   OLLAMA_NUM_PARALLEL=1 ollama serve # one request at a time = bigger KV cache
#   OLLAMA_FLASH_ATTENTION=1 ollama serve  # less KV memory on supported models


# HOW THESE COMPARE TO ANTHROPIC'S FRONTIER MODELS (HAIKU, SONNET, OPUS)
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# TL;DR: the gap is large, but the small models can substitute for
# narrow, well-defined tasks if you set expectations right.
#
# the weight class reality: frontier models (Haiku 4.5, Sonnet 4.6,
# Opus 4.7) are estimated at hundreds of billions of parameters and
# trained on trillions of tokens. a 7-8B local is roughly 1-3% the
# parameter count of frontier-class. even HAIKU 4.5 — Anthropic's
# smallest current model — substantially outperforms any 7-8B local on
# MMLU-Pro, GPQA, HumanEval, MATH, etc. Sonnet and Opus are another
# tier above that.
#
# WHERE LOCAL 7-8B IS "GOOD ENOUGH" TO ACTUALLY USE
#   - single-turn factual Q&A on common topics
#   - bash / python / SQL one-liners and small functions
#   - boilerplate (CRUD endpoints, config files, regex)
#   - summarization of short documents
#   - format conversion (JSON <-> YAML, markdown tables)
#   - tab-completion-style code assist in an editor (human reviews each)
#
# WHERE THE GAP BITES YOU
#   - multi-step reasoning that requires holding a plan together
#   - reading a large codebase and proposing cross-file changes
#   - tool use / agentic workflows — 7-8Bs are unreliable callers
#   - long-context retrieval beyond ~16k tokens (recall degrades fast)
#   - hard math / proofs / olympiad problems
#   - subtle instruction following (negative constraints, output schemas)
#   - refusal calibration and safety
#
# PER-MODEL TAKE
#
#   qwen2.5:7b
#     analog:    a noticeably weaker Haiku for general chat
#     pitch:     best general-purpose pick in the 7B class. strong
#                reasoning-for-size, Apache 2.0, 32k-128k context (recall
#                drops well before that). still well behind Haiku 4.5 on
#                multi-step tasks.
#
#   llama3.1:8b
#     analog:    similar tier to qwen2.5:7b, slightly weaker overall but
#                better tool-use formatting
#     pitch:     Meta's broad-coverage workhorse. native 128k context
#                (recall shaky past ~16k). good for chat and function-
#                calling experimentation. behind Qwen on math/code.
#
#   qwen2.5-coder:7b
#     analog:    a weaker Haiku on code, a much weaker Sonnet
#     pitch:     the standout small code model. on HumanEval-style
#                problems it gets surprisingly close to frontier (mid-
#                high 80s % vs ~95% for Sonnet 4.6). falls apart on
#                multi-file edits, real-world refactors, ambiguous
#                specs. genuinely useful as an in-editor completion
#                engine.
#
#   codellama:7b
#     analog:    a weaker Haiku from 2023
#     pitch:     SUPERSEDED. released Aug 2023, weaker than every model
#                above, no instruction-following advantage. keep only if
#                you specifically need its `code-infill` mode. otherwise
#                replace with qwen2.5-coder:7b.
#
# CONCRETE RULE OF THUMB
#   - tasks where Sonnet/Opus would think 10+ seconds and write 200+
#     lines: DON'T USE 7B LOCALS, they will get it wrong in subtle ways.
#   - tasks where Haiku would respond in 2 seconds with a short snippet:
#     7B LOCALS CAN OFTEN DO IT, with a higher error rate you'll need
#     to catch.
#   - privacy-sensitive workflows where you'd otherwise not be able to
#     send the data: THE QUESTION CHANGES — a 70%-as-good local beats
#     not using AI at all.
#
# the honest framing isn't "local vs frontier" — it's "local plus a
# human reviewer vs frontier with less review". for code completion
# in a tight feedback loop, a 7B model wins on latency and cost. for
# complex reasoning where you'd trust the output, frontier wins
# decisively.
#
# see also: [[anthropic-models]] for current Claude 4.x lineup and
#           when to pick each.


# WHAT SETUP IS REQUIRED FOR A LOCAL HAIKU-CLASS MODEL?
# -----------------------------------------------------
#
# HONEST UPFRONT: no local model currently matches Haiku 4.5 capability-
# for-capability. the closest open-weights contenders (Llama 3.3 70B,
# Qwen 2.5 72B, DeepSeek-V3) approach Haiku on some tasks but lag on
# others. "Haiku-class" is aspirational — and the hardware bill scales
# accordingly.
#
# TIER 1 — "CLOSE, NOT EQUAL" (~$2-5K)
# the cheapest path to running a 70B-class model.
#   - 2x used RTX 3090 24 GB ($800-1000 each) -> 48 GB VRAM via model
#     split. or 1x RTX 4090/5090 (24/32 GB) + 64 GB system RAM for
#     overflow.
#   - runs Llama 3.3 70B or Qwen 2.5 72B at Q4_K_M (~40 GB weights),
#     ~10-20 tok/s.
#   - hits maybe 60-80% of Haiku on general tasks; weaker on long-
#     context, tool use, multi-step reasoning.
#   - ~400-600 W under load, audible fans, real heat. needs a desktop
#     case.
#
# TIER 2 — "COMFORTABLE 70B" (~$5-10K)
# single big card, 70B at high quant with long context.
#   - NVIDIA RTX 6000 Ada 48 GB (~$6800 new, $4-5K used), or A6000 48
#     GB (used $3-4K).
#   - or NVIDIA DGX Spark (formerly Project DIGITS, ~$3K, 128 GB unified
#     memory, released 2025) — designed exactly for this; runs 70B
#     comfortably, slower than a discrete GPU but much less hassle.
#   - or Mac Studio M3 Max 96-128 GB ($4-6K) — slower but quiet, low-
#     power, plug-and-play.
#   - Llama 3.3 70B at Q6/Q8 with 32k+ context, ~20-30 tok/s on the
#     6000 Ada.
#   - 80-90% of Haiku on general tasks; still trails on tool use and
#     complex agentic flows.
#
# TIER 3 — "ACTUALLY FRONTIER-ISH LOCALLY" (~$7-15K)
# realistic path to running a true frontier-tier MoE model at home.
#   - Mac Studio M3 Ultra 256-512 GB unified memory ($7-10K) — runs
#     DeepSeek-V3 671B at Q4 (~350 GB on disk, ~370 GB resident) at
#     5-15 tok/s. cheapest way to have a genuinely frontier-class model
#     locally; slow but it's THERE.
#   - alternative: 2x DGX Spark in cluster (~$6K, 256 GB combined) —
#     same idea, all-NVIDIA stack.
#   - first tier where you can credibly say "I'm running a Haiku-or-
#     better model at home". caveat: prompt-processing speed on Apple
#     Silicon is much slower than NVIDIA, so first-token latency feels
#     sluggish on long inputs.
#
# TIER 4 — "DATACENTER AT HOME" ($30K+)
#   - 4-8x H100 80 GB, or 2x AMD MI300X 192 GB, or a refurb DGX H100.
#   - runs Llama 3.1 405B at high precision, DeepSeek-V3 at FP8,
#     frontier-tier reasoning models at usable speed.
#   - where you genuinely match frontier inference quality and speed.
#   - power: 3-10 kW. you're paying for a dedicated 240V circuit.
#
# THE COST REALITY CHECK
# Haiku 4.5 via Anthropic API runs roughly $1/MTok in, $5/MTok out.
# heavy personal use ≈ ~$30-150/month. even Tier 1 hardware at $3K
# takes 2-7 years to amortize against API spend, BEFORE electricity.
# the case for local ISN'T COST — it's:
#   1. privacy — code / docs / conversations never leave your network
#   2. offline / air-gapped use (labs, secure envs, planes)
#   3. no rate limits or content-policy refusals
#   4. stable behavior — your model doesn't change underneath you
#   5. fine-tuning — adapt the weights to your data
# if none of those apply, the API is the rational choice and it isn't
# close.
#
# THE PRAGMATIC STEP-UP FROM AN 8 GB LAPTOP
# cheapest serious upgrade: a desktop with 1x RTX 5090 32 GB or a used
# 3090 + 64 GB RAM for ~$2-3K. that puts you in Tier 1 and is the
# highest jump-per-dollar you'll see. going to Tier 2/3 is a bigger
# commitment of money and physical space, and the gains over Tier 1
# are meaningful but not enormous unless you specifically need long
# context or MoE-class reasoning.


# WHAT SETUP IS REQUIRED FOR A LOCAL SONNET-CLASS MODEL?
# ------------------------------------------------------
#
# HONEST UPFRONT: matching Sonnet-class locally is meaningfully harder
# than matching Haiku-class. no current open-weights model genuinely
# matches Sonnet 4.6. closest contenders: DeepSeek-V3 671B (MoE, 37B
# active), DeepSeek-R1, Llama 3.1 405B, Llama 4 Maverick (400B MoE).
# they approach Sonnet on benchmarks but lag on real-world tool use,
# multi-step refactoring, and effective long-context recall. so the
# hardware bill below buys you "Sonnet-ish on most tasks", not "Sonnet
# equivalent".
#
# the Haiku -> Sonnet jump in open-weights land roughly means going
# from a 70B dense to a 400B+ MoE. memory requirements 5-10x from there.
#
# TIER A — "SONNET-ISH VIA MOE" (~$10-15K)
# the cheapest entry point.
#   - Mac Studio M3 Ultra 512 GB unified memory (~$10K, released 2025) —
#     runs DeepSeek-V3 671B at Q4 (~370 GB resident), Llama 3.1 405B at
#     Q6-Q8, or Llama 4 Maverick at Q8.
#   - ~5-15 tok/s generation; prompt processing is the bottleneck (long
#     inputs feel sluggish — 30-60 s to first token on 32k context).
#   - hits ~75-85% of Sonnet on general tasks; closer on raw code,
#     further on agentic / tool-heavy workflows.
#   - THE ONLY "single appliance" path to Sonnet-class locally. anything
#     else gets complicated fast.
#
# TIER B — "COMFORTABLE SONNET-CLASS ON NVIDIA" ($20-50K)
#   - 4x RTX 6000 Ada 48 GB (~$28K) -> 192 GB VRAM. runs Llama 3.1 405B
#     at Q4 cleanly with usable context, or DeepSeek-V3 at heavy quant
#     (Q2/Q3 — quality drops).
#   - or 2x H100 80 GB ($40-50K) -> 160 GB HBM3. same envelope, much
#     faster.
#   - or 2x AMD MI300X 192 GB ($30-50K) -> 384 GB HBM3. best memory
#     headroom in this tier; ROCm tooling is the catch.
#   - ~30-60 tok/s on 405B Q4, 80-150 tok/s on smaller models. fast
#     prompt processing — long-context feels frontier-like.
#   - power: 1.5-3 kW. real desktop / open-frame rig, dedicated 20A or
#     30A circuit, real cooling.
#
# TIER C — "PROPER INFERENCE RIG" ($50-150K)
#   - 4-8x H100 80 GB ($50-120K) — the canonical setup. runs DeepSeek-V3
#     at Q8/FP8, Llama 3.1 405B at full BF16, high-throughput batched
#     serving (can host for a team).
#   - or 4x MI300X ($60-100K) — 768 GB HBM3, runs everything above at
#     higher precision.
#   - or 2x NVIDIA B200 / Blackwell (when supply normalizes) — same
#     envelope, lower power.
#   - 100-300+ tok/s, 8k-32k context at full quality, can fine-tune.
#   - 5-10 kW, 240V dedicated circuit, real noise (server-grade fans).
#
# TIER D — "DATACENTER AT HOME / SMALL TEAM" ($150K+)
#   - DGX H100 / DGX H200 node ($300K+), or 8x MI300X.
#   - frontier MoE at FP8/FP16 with full context, fine-tuning, can
#     serve a small org.
#   - at this point seriously consider whether RENTING from Lambda /
#     Modal / RunPod isn't 10x cheaper for hours-per-day usage.
#
# THE COST REALITY CHECK
# Sonnet 4.6 via Anthropic API is roughly $3/MTok in, $15/MTok out.
# heavy personal use ≈ $200-500/month; small team easily $2-5K/month.
#   - Tier A ($10K)  breakeven ≈ 2-4 years vs heavy personal API spend.
#   - Tier B ($30K)  breakeven ≈ 6-18 months vs team-scale API spend.
#   - Tier C ($100K) only sane if serving multiple users continuously,
#                    or hard data-residency / air-gap requirements.
# cost is essentially never the winning argument until you're serving
# a team or running 24/7. the case for local is the same as Haiku-class
# (privacy / offline / no rate limits / stable weights / fine-tuning),
# just at higher stakes.
#
# THE PRAGMATIC ANSWER
#   - want to TRY Sonnet-class locally without committing real money:
#     Mac Studio M3 Ultra 512 GB at ~$10K is the only sane consumer
#     entry. slower than NVIDIA, but it actually fits the weights
#     without complicated rigging; resale value holds well if you bail.
#   - real team-scale use case: 2x H100 80 GB is the proven sweet spot —
#     frontier-class throughput on 405B, room for fine-tuning,
#     manageable in a colo rack.
#   - solo: STOP HERE. Tier B+ for one person is almost never the right
#     call vs paying Anthropic by the token.
#
# the consumer hardware curve is bending toward this getting much
# cheaper over the next 18-24 months. M4 Ultra Mac Studios, NVIDIA
# DGX Spark cluster configs, AMD Strix Halo (128 GB unified APU, 2025)
# are all aimed at this market. if your need isn't urgent, waiting a
# year halves the price.


# WHAT SETUP IS REQUIRED FOR A LOCAL OPUS-CLASS MODEL?
# ----------------------------------------------------
#
# HONEST UPFRONT: a true Opus 4.7 equivalent does not currently exist
# in open weights, period. the Sonnet question had close-but-not-quite
# contenders (DeepSeek-V3, Llama 3.1 405B, Llama 4 Maverick). the Opus
# question doesn't really have any — the gap from Sonnet to Opus in
# agentic reasoning, long-horizon planning, hardest-tier coding,
# creative judgment, and refusal calibration is exactly where open-
# weights are weakest. so what the hardware below buys you is "the
# best open-weight model at full precision with frontier throughput",
# which is approximately Sonnet+ on benchmarks and NOTICEABLY BELOW
# Opus on the workflows that justify reaching for Opus in the first
# place.
#
# closest contenders to aim for: DeepSeek-R1 671B at full precision
# with extended thinking, DeepSeek-V3 671B at FP8/BF16, Llama 3.1 405B
# at BF16, Llama 4 Behemoth (~2T total MoE, if/when it ships).
#
# the Sonnet -> Opus jump is less about another 10x memory and more
# about needing FRONTIER-TIER THROUGHPUT so extended-thinking and
# agentic workloads aren't punitively slow. that moves you from
# "consumer-adjacent" into datacenter-grade infrastructure.
#
# TIER I — "THE HONEST 'APPROACHING OPUS' FLOOR" (~$15-30K)
# same hardware as Sonnet Tier A, running the same models — there is no
# $15K leap to Opus-class.
#   - Mac Studio M3 Ultra 512 GB (~$10-12K) — runs DeepSeek-V3/R1 at
#     Q4-Q6, 5-15 tok/s.
#   - or DGX Spark cluster (4x at ~$12K, 512 GB combined) — same
#     envelope, all-NVIDIA stack.
#   - hits ~70-85% of Opus on simple chat/code, 30-50% on hard agentic
#     / multi-step / long-context tasks. the Opus-tier workflows are
#     EXACTLY the ones this tier can't keep up with.
#   - if your goal is "Opus-class at home for solo use", this tier is
#     the MOST you should spend — and it still isn't Opus.
#
# TIER II — "REAL FRONTIER HARDWARE" ($100-300K)
# where you start running frontier open-weight models at full precision
# with usable throughput.
#   - 8x NVIDIA H100 80 GB ($120-150K) -> 640 GB HBM3. runs DeepSeek-
#     V3/R1 at FP8 with full context, fine-tuning, batch-serves a team.
#   - or 8x H200 141 GB ($200K+) -> 1.1 TB HBM3e. headroom for Llama 4
#     Behemoth or future 1T+ models.
#   - or 4x NVIDIA B200 192 GB (when supply normalizes) -> 768 GB
#     HBM3e, lower power per FLOP.
#   - or 8x AMD MI300X 192 GB ($150-250K) -> 1.5 TB HBM3. biggest
#     memory pool in this tier; ROCm tooling is the catch.
#   - 100-300+ tok/s on 405B/V3, 8k-32k context at full quality,
#     fine-tuning on the table.
#   - 10-15 kW. server room, real cooling, 240V industrial, ~$500-1000
#     per month electricity alone.
#   - STILL NOT Opus-equivalent on the hardest workflows, but it's the
#     closest you can buy.
#
# TIER III — "GENUINE FRONTIER INFRASTRUCTURE" ($500K-3M+)
#   - multiple DGX H100/H200 nodes, or NVIDIA GB200 NVL72 rack (~$3M
#     for a full config), or B200/B300 clusters.
#   - hyperscaler/lab infrastructure. can run models bigger than what's
#     publicly released, fine-tune frontier-scale, serve hundreds of
#     users.
#   - at this scale YOU SHOULD NOT BE BUYING. rent equivalent capacity
#     from CoreWeave / Lambda / Crusoe / a colo provider on demand —
#     order of magnitude cheaper for hours-per-day usage and you don't
#     deal with depreciation as H200 -> B200 -> Rubin keeps compressing.
#
# THE COST REALITY CHECK (sharper here than Sonnet)
# Opus 4.7 via Anthropic API is roughly $15/MTok in, $75/MTok out.
# heavy personal use ≈ $500-2000/month; team workloads $5-20K/month.
#   - Tier I  ($15K)  breakeven ≈ 1-3 years vs heavy personal Opus
#                     spend — BUT IT'S NOT RUNNING OPUS-CLASS quality,
#                     so this isn't really a substitution.
#   - Tier II ($150K) breakeven ≈ 1-2 years vs sustained team Opus
#                     spend, ignoring electricity/colo/staff time.
#                     interesting at small-org scale with privacy reqs.
#   - Tier III ($1M+) only makes sense if you're a lab/startup doing
#                     fine-tuning research, or serving 24/7 prod.
# the case for local at Opus-tier is NARROWER than at lower tiers:
# privacy, air-gapped requirements, hard data residency, very heavy
# fine-tuning. for everything else, the API is so obviously the
# rational choice that the hardware conversation is almost academic.
#
# THE PRAGMATIC ANSWER
#   - DON'T try to match Opus-class locally as an individual. you
#     can't, and the closest attempt (Tier I) doesn't actually
#     substitute for the workflows you'd want Opus for.
#   - real privacy-constrained team use case: plan for Tier II in
#     12-18 months. hardware is depreciating fast (Blackwell B200
#     deliveries in 2025 dropped used H100 prices ~30%; AMD MI325X /
#     MI350 series in 2025-2026 keep compressing prices). waiting is
#     correct unless you're paying $20K+/month on Opus API today.
#   - WATCH-FOR SIGNAL: if Qwen 4, DeepSeek-V4, Llama 5, or some
#     yet-unannounced open-weights release in 2026 genuinely matches
#     Opus on agentic benchmarks, the Tier I/II conversation changes
#     overnight. until then, Opus-class workloads -> Anthropic API
#     is correct for ~99% of users.
#
# HONEST SUMMARY OF THE FULL LADDER
#   Haiku-class    reachable for $3-10K (Tier 1-2 above)
#   Sonnet-class   approachable for $10-50K with caveats (Tier A-B)
#   Opus-class     NOT REACHABLE at home today at any consumer-feasible
#                  budget. the hardware that gets close is also the
#                  hardware you'd rent rather than own.
